    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "1e1cc9bb_91f51913",
        "filename": "util/linux/process_memory_test.cc",
        "patchSetId": 12
      },
      "lineNbr": 37,
      "author": {
        "id": 1174099
      },
      "writtenOn": "2017-03-27T18:06:41Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "I see that you’ve done error checking of pid_ elsewhere, but it should really all be consolidated here, at the call that might fail. You don’t want someone to come along and add something else to the constructor and then wind up with undetected ambiguous failure modes.\n\nIf pid_ \u003c 0, stop and fail the test right here.\n\nIn test code, it’d be acceptable to leave the failure-prone work in a constructor and register the failure via an EXPECT_*() or ADD_FAILURE(). For example, this should work\n\n  pid_ \u003d fork();\n  if (pid_ \u003c 0) {\n    ADD_FAILURE() \u003c\u003c ErrorMessage(\"fork\");\n    return;\n  }\n  if (pid_ \u003d\u003d 0) {\n    // …\n\nbut you’ll want to call testing::Test::HasFailure() back where the class is used to abort the test early in case the constructor failed:\n\n  ScopedChildProcess child;\n  ASSERT_FALSE(testing::Test::HasFailure());\n\nThis is a little quirky, partially because you can’t ASSERT_*() your way out of a constructor. Given all of this, you may find it clearer to just use an Initialize(), even though handling failures in this way in a constructor is OK.",
      "revId": "909caee55fa90e52db9d42c9310b43383793ae29",
      "serverId": "3ce6091f-6c88-37e8-8c75-72f92ae8dfba",
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "ddc59e96_4ff79d7b",
        "filename": "util/linux/process_memory_test.cc",
        "patchSetId": 12
      },
      "lineNbr": 44,
      "author": {
        "id": 1174099
      },
      "writtenOn": "2017-03-27T18:06:41Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "“const” is a good habit to be in for our codebase and Chrome in general. And this should be named for the underlying variable, and not for getpid() which can easily be confused with the system call of the same name. So:\n\n  pid_t pid() const { return pid_; }",
      "revId": "909caee55fa90e52db9d42c9310b43383793ae29",
      "serverId": "3ce6091f-6c88-37e8-8c75-72f92ae8dfba",
      "unresolved": true
